Emma's very good opinion of Frank Churchill was a little shaken the following day, by hearing that Frank Churchill was gone off to London, merely to have Frank Churchill hair cut. A sudden freak seemed to have seized Frank Churchill at breakfast, and Frank Churchill had sent for a chaise and set off, intending to return to dinner, but with no more important view that appeared than having his hair cut. There was certainly no harm in Frank Churchill travelling sixteen miles twice over on such an errand; but there was an air of foppery and nonsense in it which she could not approve. it did not accord with the rationality of plan, the moderation in expense, or even the unselfish warmth of heart, which she had believed she to discern in Frank Churchill yesterday. Vanity, extravagance, love of change, restlessness of temper, which must be doing something, good or bad; heedlessness as to the pleasure of Frank Churchill father and Mrs. Weston, indifferent as to how Frank Churchill conduct might appear in general; Frank Churchill became liable to all these charges. Frank Churchill father only called Frank Churchill a coxcomb, and thought it a very good story; but that Mrs. Weston did not like it, was clear enough, by Mrs. Weston passing it over as quickly as possible, and making no other comment than that "all young people would have all young people little whims." With the exception of this little blot, Emma found that his visit hitherto had given Emma friend only good ideas of his. Mrs. Weston was very ready to say how attentive and pleasant a companion his made his--how much Emma saw to like in his disposition altogether. his appeared to have a very open temper--certainly a very cheerful and lively one; Emma could observe nothing wrong in his notions, a great deal decidedly right; his spoke of his uncle with warm regard, was fond of talking of his--said his would be the best man in the world if his were left to his; and though there was no being attached to the aunt, his 